body:
The following code:

```

module verilator_blocking
  (
   input logic [2:0] state,
   output logic [31:0] b,
   input clk
   );

   function logic [31:0 ] toto () ;
      logic [31:0] res;
      res = 10;

      return res;
   endfunction

   always @(posedge clk) begin
      b <= 0;
      if(state != 2) begin
         b <= toto();
      end
   end

endmodule;
```

generates the following warning since version 5:

```
verilator --no-timing --lint-only -Wall verilator_blocking.sv
%Warning-BLKSEQ: verilator_blocking.sv:10:11: Blocking assignment '=' in sequential logic process
                                            : ... Suggest using delayed assignment '<='
   10 |       res = 10;
      |           ^
                 ... For warning description see https://verilator.org/warn/BLKSEQ?v=5.010
                 ... Use "/* verilator lint_off BLKSEQ */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
%Error: Exiting due to 1 warning(s)

```

This looks like a bug to me. I don't even think functions can have non-blocking assignments anyway.
